SIMPLE: putrefaction
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Putrefaction
<hw>Pu`tre*fac"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>putrefactio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>putr⟦eacute⟧faction</ets>. See
<er>Putrefy</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act or the process of
putrefying; the offensive decay of albuminous or other matter.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Putrefaction is a complex phenomenon involving a
multiplicity of chemical reactions, always accompanied by, and without
doubt caused by, bacteria and vibriones; hence, putrefaction is a form
of fermentation, and is sometimes called <xex>putrefaction
fermentative</xex>. Putrefaction is not possible under conditions that
preclude the development of living organisms. Many of the products of
putrefaction are powerful poisons, and are called <xex>cadaveric
poisons</xex>, or <xex>ptoma⟦ium⟧nes</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The condition of being putrefied; also, that which
putrefied.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Putrefaction's</xex> breath.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shelley.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Putrefactive</ent>⟦br⟧
